ce:caption.ce:simple-para:
Calculation equations of the electrical and mechanical parameters for the analysis of the electromechanical cell behavior. All parameters were determined at the m th check-up, whereas the first check-up cycle means BoL (
m = 1
).

ce:section.ce:para:
The extent to which the new findings can be applied to the design of mechanical batteries was also analyzed. It was found that the energy density could be increased in all investigated cells by pressure. Due to the increased expansion, which could be reduced by pressure, an increase in energy density of up to 6% at BoL and more than 12% at EoT could be achieved for Si-C 34. The optimum pressure depends on the application scenario (service life vs. performance) and the silicon material used (Si-C vs. SiO



                              x


                     ). The lifetime was significantly limited at the resulting pressures of up to 3 MPa, demonstrating the potential for optimization; however, the IR curve could also be positively influenced by pressure, which may be of interest for high-performance applications in which lifetime is not a major concern.
